@node sect0 "Name"
nspark - unpack Archimedes archives 
@endnode

@node sect1 "Synopsis"
@{b}nspark@{ub} [ @{b}options@{ub} ] archive [ @{b}file ...@{ub} ] 
@endnode

@node sect2 "Description"
The current version of @{b}nspark@{ub} is 1.7.5 
 @{b}Nspark@{ub} can unpack the specified Archimedes-format @{b}archive,@{ub} list its contents or tests its integrity. 
 Nspark's main features are: 
 o Supports all archive methods used by !Spark 1 and 2. The old version didn't support "Squashing" and used to handle "Compressed" archives by using the UNIX uncompress program. The new version supports both these and has them built-in, allowing easier porting to other OS's. 
 o Supports ArcFS format archives. 
 o Supports Cyclic Redundancy Checking (CRC). The integrity of an archive can now be checked without having to unarchive it. 
 o Supports verbose option to allow archive file details to be displayed (time/date or exec/load address, size, type). 
 o Supports selective file unarchiving, so the whole archive needn't be unarchived if not all the files are wanted). 
 o Supports user-prompting before overwriting a file, allowing the user to @{"either (1)" link %s.%seither1/main} overwrite the file, (2) overwrite all the files, (3) unarchive the file to a different name, @{"or (4)" link %s.%sor4/main} not to unarchive the file at all. 
 o Supports file-stamping so the date and time of the file, when unarchived, matches the date and time it was archived (not 4.2BSD or SysV.2 as these systems lack vital library functions). 
 I have not included support for creating !Spark archives, and I am not really sure if I need to as: (1) !Spark for RISC OS is cheap (#5.99 from David Pilling), (2) !SparkPlug can unpack archives created with zip (which is available in source form for UNIX, VMS and MSDOS), and (3) it's a lot of work. Let me know what you think. 
 @{i}Options:@{ui} 

· -x@{lindent 3}
Extract the given @{b}file,@{ub} or all files if none are specified. @{lindent 0}

· -u@{lindent 3}
Equivalent to -x. @{lindent 0}

· -t@{lindent 3}
Test archive integrity by simulating extraction and checking the CRCs (Cyclic Redundancy Checks). @{lindent 0}

· -l@{lindent 3}
List archive contents. @{lindent 0}

· -q@{lindent 3}
Quiet.  Displays less information when listing, testing or extracting. @{lindent 0}

· -f@{lindent 3}
Force file overwrite if a file already exists with the same name as the one being extracted. If not using -f then you are prompted whether you want to overwrite the original, skip this file, give it a different name, or overwrite this and all others that already exist. @{lindent 0}

· -s@{lindent 3}
No filestamp. Does not set the timestamp when extracting files. @{lindent 0}

· -v@{lindent 3}
Verbose.  Gives full details when listing or extracting archives. @{lindent 0}

· -R@{lindent 3}
Retry if archive is corrupt.  If a bad header is found then nspark will search the archive until another header if found, rather than giving up. @{lindent 0}

· -L<name>@{lindent 3}
Set name of log file to @{b}name.@{ub} @{lindent 0}

· -T@{lindent 3}
Append file type to name, in the same way as Tar or NFS.  For example Text files (filetype &FFF) have ,fff appended when extracted. @{lindent 0}

· -C@{lindent 3}
Create lowercase filenames.  Useful on machines where the case of filenames is significant (eg. UNIX), this option forces all extracted filenames to be lowercase. @{lindent 0}


@endnode

@node sect3 "Bugs"
Filestamping is not supported under 4.2BSD or SysV2 (as no @{"mktime(3)" link %s.%smktime3/main} or @{"timelocal(3)" link %s.%stimelocal3/main} functions exist under these systems).  To correct this I could write my own or port the one from 386BSD (save that for a rainy day). 
 Doesn't support MSDOS yet.  Working on that. 
 If compiled with GCC (v1.42) it core dumps when trying to test (or unarchive ?) a corrupt archive file.  This doesn't happen when compiled with the UNIX pcc. 
@endnode

@node sect4 "Notes"
@{b}Nspark@{ub} is in the public domain. It is currently being maintained by arb (arb@comp.lancs.ac.uk). 
@endnode

